:"1295","1392":"1392","1270":"1270","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","Cir 1292":"1292","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","about 1325":"circa 1325","about 1300":"circa 1300","about 1330":"circa 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Haccombe, Devon, England":"Haccombe, Devon, England","Bideford, Devon, England":"Bideford, Devon, England","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovelly, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"en":{"about 1300–about 1330":"about 1300–about 1330","1295–Female":"1295–Deceased","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1302–1392":"1302–1392","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1325–1368":"1325–1368","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1274–1303":"1274–1303","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1392":"1392","1270":"1270","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","Cir 1292":"1292","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","about 1325":"about 1325","about 1300":"about 1300","about 1330":"about 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Haccombe, Devon, England":"Haccombe, Devon, England","Bideford, Devon, England":"Bideford, Devon, England","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovelly, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cary","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish (Donegal and Westmeath) and English: variant of   Carey  .","French: variant of   Carry   2."],"variants":[{"name":"Decorah","meanings":["Americanized form of <b>de Carrie</b>, itself an altered form of French <b>Decary</b>, a variant of   Cary   2, with fused preposition <i>de</i> ‘of’. It is found mainly among the Ho-Chunk (i.e. Winnebago) Native American people in WI.","History: The progenitor of the Decorahs was a French soldier, Joseph Sabrevoir de Carrie, who in 1729 settled for a time among the Winnebagos on Doty Island, WI, and married an Indian woman, known in English as Glory of the Morning. Decorah, a city in IA, is named after one of their descendants, Waukon Decorah (<i>c.</i> 1780–1868), a chief of the Winnebago."]},{"name":"Carey","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Ciardha</b>, a midland surname meaning ‘descendant of <i>Ciardha</i>’, a personal name derived from <i>ciar</i> ‘dark, black’. See   Kerry  .","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Fhiachra</b> ‘son of <i>Fiachra</i>’.","English: from Carey Barton in Devon or Castle Cary, Lytes Cary, Cary Fitzpaine, or Babcary, all in Somerset, named for the rivers on which they stand; both river names probably derive from the Celtic root <i>car-</i> ‘love, liking’, perhaps with the meaning ‘pleasant stream’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":15,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":28,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir William Cary was born about 1300, in Devon, England, his father, John de Kary, was 31 and his mother, Phillippa Archdeacon, was 27. He married Margaret de Boson in 1324, in Clovelly, Devon, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died about 1330, in Bideford, Devon, England, at the age of 32."},"et":{"about 1300–about 1330":"umbes 1300–umbes 1330","1295–Female":"1295–Surnud","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1302–1392":"1302–1392","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1325–1368":"1325–1368","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1274–1303":"1274–1303","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1392":"1392","1270":"1270","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","Cir 1292":"1292","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","about 1325":"umbes 1325","about 1300":"umbes 1300","about 1330":"umbes 1330","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Haccombe, Devon, England":"Haccombe, Devon, England","Bideford, Devon, England":"Bideford, Devon, England","Clovelly, Devon, England":"Clovelly, Devon, England","Devon, England":"Devon, England","Castle Cary, Somerset, England":"Castle Cary, Somerset, England"},"fi":{"about 1300–about 1330":"noin 1300–noin 1330","1295–Female":"1295–Kuollut","1300–1330":"1300–1330","1302–1392":"1302–1392","1304–1327":"1304–1327","1325–1368":"1325–1368","1270–1304":"1270–1304","1274–1303":"1274–1303","1330":"1330","1274":"1274","1295":"1295","1392":"1392","1270":"1270","1327":"1327","1304":"1304","Cir 1292":"1292","1315":"1315","1303":"1303","1325":"1325","1324":"1324","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1300":"1300","about 1325":"noin 1325","about 1300":"noin 1300","about 1330":"noin 1330","